      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Body Corporate Building Insurance in Queensland: What Unit Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Understanding what the body corporate insures and what it does not is basic knowledge for anyone selling a Queensland apartment or townhouse. Buyers and their lenders will check. You should too.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell a unit or townhouse in Queensland, the body corporate records search is one of the first things a buyer's solicitor requests. Inside that search is the building insurance certificate of currency. If the building is underinsured or the policy has lapsed, buyers and their lenders will notice. Understanding what that insurance covers, and what it does not, puts you in a better position to answer questions and avoid surprises late in a campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the body corporate building insurance covers</h2>
      <p>Body corporate building insurance in Queensland covers the structure of the building and the common property. This includes the shell of the building, the roof, external walls, shared facilities such as the pool, gym, and carpark, and all common area infrastructure. The policy protects the collective asset of the scheme from risks including fire, storm damage, and other insured events specified in the policy.</p>

      <p>The insurance is managed by the body corporate, not by individual lot owners. The premium is funded through the administration fund levies that all owners pay. A meaningful portion of your quarterly levy goes directly to funding this insurance, which is why levy amounts at newer or high-rise buildings can be significantly higher than at older, smaller schemes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the body corporate building insurance does not cover</h2>
      <p>The body corporate policy does not cover the contents of individual lots. This includes furniture, appliances, and personal property inside a unit. It does not cover fixtures and improvements that lot owners have made within their own unit, such as a kitchen renovation, new bathroom tiling, or custom built-ins. Each lot owner is responsible for insuring what is inside their four walls, including any structural improvements they have made beyond the original building specification.</p>

      <p>As a seller, this means your own contents insurance remains your responsibility until settlement day. The body corporate policy will not protect your personal property if something happens to your unit during the campaign period. Maintain your own policy and do not assume the building insurance has you covered in any scenario that involves the interior of your lot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Replacement value versus market value</h2>
      <p>This distinction matters more than most sellers realise. The body corporate building insurance should be set at full replacement value, meaning the cost to demolish and rebuild the entire structure from scratch. This figure is often significantly higher than the market value of the individual lots within the scheme, particularly for older Brisbane buildings where construction costs have risen sharply.</p>

      <p>An insurer that sets the policy at a figure based on market value rather than replacement value creates an underinsurance risk. If the building is destroyed and the payout does not cover full reconstruction, lot owners face a levy shortfall. Buyers and their lenders understand this, which is why a well-advised buyer will scrutinise the insured sum. If the insurance looks inadequate, it becomes a negotiating point or a reason to walk away.</p>

      <p>If you are unsure whether your building is adequately insured, the body corporate manager can provide this information. It is publicly accessible through the records search in any case, so better to understand it before a buyer's solicitor raises it mid-campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Active claims and what they mean for your sale</h2>
      <p>If the building has an active insurance claim at the time you sell, that information will appear in the body corporate records search. This could relate to storm damage to the roof, a pool deck that needs remediation, or any other building matter that is currently being managed through the insurer. Buyers see this and their reaction will depend on the nature and scale of the claim.</p>

      <p>A minor claim for a small repair is unlikely to affect your sale. A large, unresolved structural claim is a different matter. Buyers may ask for a price reduction, insert a special condition, or walk away if the exposure is unclear. The honest approach is to disclose what you know and let your solicitor advise on how to handle it contractually. Attempting to conceal a known material defect creates far greater legal exposure than the claim itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to check before you list</h2>
      <p>Before marketing your unit, pull a copy of the body corporate records from the body corporate manager. Confirm the current certificate of currency is up to date, that the insured sum reflects realistic replacement value, and that there are no active claims that would surprise a buyer. If the body corporate has not reviewed the insured sum recently, flag this with the committee. Addressing it before the records search is ordered is far better than having a buyer's solicitor raise it as a concern during negotiation.</p>

      <p>Your agent should understand body corporate documentation well enough to give you a plain-English read of what buyers are likely to flag. If they cannot do that, you are working with someone who does not regularly sell in this segment of the market.</p>

